at this point.

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:46.820
And finally, think
about reaching out

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:51.200
to your tester community to
gather very specific feedback.

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:54.815
This is your chance to ask them
what works, what didn't work,

00:07:54.815 --> 00:07:55.850
and how do we improve.

00:07:58.430 --> 00:08:01.310
Next, open testing.

00:08:01.310 --> 00:08:04.190
Once a game is technically solid
and your main gameplay hooks

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:07.010
are built in, it's time
to think about expanding

00:08:07.010 --> 00:08:09.500
your test to more
players in preparation

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:11.750
for your big launch.

00:08:11.750 --> 00:08:15.980
Open testing allows your game to
be discoverable and installable

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:18.430
on the Play Store
and for players,

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:21.380
after a developer defined
cap, to opt in and install

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:23.250
your game.

00:08:23.250 --> 00:08:25.910
Players won't be able to leave
ratings until the game fully

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:28.730
launches, but can provide
anonymous feedback

00:08:28.730 --> 00:08:32.000
to the developer at any time.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.309
Open testing comes
in two flavors,

00:08:34.309 --> 00:08:38.240
depending on the
state of your game.

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:40.470
If you don't have a
production release already,

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:43.330
or in the same country as
you are running your test in,

00:08:43.330 --> 00:08:45.800
users will be able to
install your game directly

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:49.160
from the Play Store
without needing to opt in.

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:51.710
We call this early access.

00:08:51.710 --> 00:08:53.480
Your game will be
tagged as unreleased,

00:08:53.480 --> 00:08:54.470
as shown in this image.

00:08:57.050 --> 00:08:59.180
If you have a production
release already--

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:02.330
for instance, you may have soft
launched in the same country--

00:09:02.330 --> 00:09:05.540
you can still continue
to use open testing.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:09.820
Existing users will continue to
get updates on the test track,

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:14.560
and new users can opt in via
a console provided web link

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:16.700
or through the card, which
is shown on the screen

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:20.870
here at the bottom of
the game's details page.

00:09:20.870 --> 00:09:23.810
Players opted into an
open test in this state

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:27.840
will see the game
tagged as Beta.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:31.380
So bringing together
these forms of testing,

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.830
of internal tests and closed
tests, you, as the developers,

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:39.630
have control over who can
install and play your game.

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:41.230
Early access tests
can be installed

00:09:41.230 --> 00:09:43.170
and discovered directly
from the Play Store

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:46.110
and are a great way to
expand your tester base,

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.590
as well as building hype
around your big launch.

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:53.940
Finally, open tests can be
used to continue testing

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:57.950
with a wide audience, even
after your production release.

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:01.140
Utilize these testers to try
out new features and tweaks

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:05.980
to your game before rolling
out to all your players.

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:09.510
Moving on-- pre-launch
reports can also

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:12.810
help developers iron out
quality and performance issues

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:15.120
prior to launch.

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:18.900
Whenever a test APK is uploaded
and nondeterministic bot

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:20.760
will crawl your game
while it's running

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.020
on a real physical device
in one of our test labs.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:26.730
Game developers have
found a lot of value

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:28.620
in the pre-launch report.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:31.560
90% of developers don't
push to production

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:35.430
if the report shows issues.

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:39.420
Demo loops goes even
further for game developers.

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:43.590
Record and upload a game demo
loop using Firebase test lab

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:48.340
and receive a PLR report on
crash and performance metrics,

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.690
including the all important
frames per second.

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:54.960
This allows you to discover
rendering issues even faster

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:58.770
and launch with
greater confidence.

00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:01.560
Half Brick Games, the
developers of titles

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:04.740
such as "Fruit Ninja"
and "Jetpack Joyride"

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:07.950
have found great
values in demo loops.

00:11:07.950 --> 00:11:09.510
They've evolved
their QA processes

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:11.880
around using PLR
demo loops, as it

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:16.020
allows them to check for
visual glitches, crashes,

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:19.290
and performance, among
many other things.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:21.840
They rely on the fact that
PLR will automatically

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:25.740
run on a wide range of
devices and device specs

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:28.050
for every test release.

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:31.150
So how did they do this?

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:33.630
Their new game, which
is "Endless Runner",

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:36.120
has a built-in
replay functionality

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:40.430
which are used to record and
save interesting game runs.

00:11:40.430 --> 00:11:43.410
With a few simple
lines of code, they

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:49.380
can instrument PLR demo loops to
run on these recorded sessions.

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:51.750
Whereas before, it was
a very manual process

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:55.710
to kick off their benchmarking,
now, with PLR demo loops,

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:59.002
it's automated for them
for every test release.

00:11:59.002 --> 00:12:00.960
They can look at these
metrics and compare them

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:03.990
to every previous
release to make sure

00:12:03.990 --> 00:12:05.880
that their game has no
regressions in terms

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:09.460
of performance.

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:11.350
Before we move
over to launching,

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:13.860
another important
aspect of pre-launch

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:17.110
is to plan your
strategy around content.

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:22.000
As such, don't be afraid to
test longer and to test earlier.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.040
Consider using longer term
metrics, like D14 and D30,

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:30.190
in order to predict
future success.

00:12:30.190 --> 00:12:33.670
Measure the rate of content
consumption during your testing

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:34.900
phase.

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:37.390
This can be useful
for planning ahead,

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:39.550
so that you have enough
content for your players

00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:43.240
when you launch until
your first big update.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.960
Also, this phase is
a great opportunity

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:49.540
to test what sort
of LiveOp events

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:51.700
will resonate with
your player base,

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:53.920
so that you can create the
content your players will

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:54.750
want to receive.

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:01.570
It is also important to consider
how different forms of testing

00:13:01.570 --> 00:13:05.050
can be used to achieve
different purposes.

00:13:05.050 --> 00:13:08.230
All testing tracks can be used
in unison with each other,

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:10.620
allowing you to target
different experiences

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:13.090
to different groups of testers.

00:13:13.090 --> 00:13:15.580
For instance, you
may want to consider

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:18.790
to run your daily builds past
your internal test track users

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:21.790
to check for regressions
at the same time

00:13:21.790 --> 00:13:26.790
as you're running a large scale
open test with early access.

00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:30.370
Closed testing can also be used
to fine tune specific gameplay

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:33.310
mechanics with a select
audience before rolling out

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:36.490
to your production users.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:42.190
Finally, you should
always keep in mind

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:45.490
that mobile games development
is an ever-changing landscape.

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:48.670
New technology is opening
up new ways to play,

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:52.750
and player expectations on
