We've gone through
some of the tools

00:35:40.110 --> 00:35:42.160
that you can take
advantage of post-launch.

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:43.900
But as we draw to
a close, I want

00:35:43.900 --> 00:35:46.000
to loop us back to the
beginning of our talk

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.160
and call out testing again.

00:35:48.160 --> 00:35:49.990
It's good to always be testing.

00:35:49.990 --> 00:35:53.110
In comparison to apps, this
can be tricky for games,

00:35:53.110 --> 00:35:55.510
as some games need users
to be on the same version

00:35:55.510 --> 00:35:57.130
to function properly.

00:35:57.130 --> 00:35:59.800
But think about how you can
effectively use Play's testing

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:02.590
tracks, which will all work
as well post-launch as they

00:36:02.590 --> 00:36:04.780
do pre-launch, to
ensure your updates

00:36:04.780 --> 00:36:07.220
live up to the quality
bar set for your game.

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:12.770
To wrap up, we've
discussed a number

00:36:12.770 --> 00:36:14.610
of tools in Play
Console you can use

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:17.600
in various stages of
your game's lifecycle.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:19.250
There's a lot going
on in mobile gaming

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:21.910
right now with
fantastic gamer growth,

00:36:21.910 --> 00:36:23.810
loads of high quality
games being released,

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:25.594
and lots of competition.

00:36:25.594 --> 00:36:27.260
It's your own fault,
as you keep raising

00:36:27.260 --> 00:36:30.620
the bar higher and higher
in terms of graphics, story,

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:31.700
and gameplay.

